{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014x5Ug2ZjwDDa7HBGe8cyrR","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→\"\"\"Reactions kernel: per-particle phase transitions, combustion, and corrosion.\n     2→\n     3→Compiles physics/kernels/reactions.cu via CuPy RawModule and provides\n     4→a function to launch K_Reactions which performs:\n     5→  - ICE -> WATER (temp > 273K)\n     6→  - LAVA -> STONE (temp < 900K)\n     7→  - WATER -> SPAWN_GAS flag (temp > 373K)\n     8→  - STEAM -> WATER (temp < 373K)\n     9→  - WOOD/OIL/GUNPOWDER -> FIRE (exposure_heat threshold)\n    10→  - Corrosion: health -= exposure_corrode * dt\n    11→  - GAS lifetime decay -> DEAD when expired\n    12→\n    13→Operates on SORTED arrays, runs after Step1 (which computes exposure)\n    14→and before Step2 (which computes forces).\n    15→\n    16→Uses shared constant memory from common.cuh:\n    17→  c_sim       -- SimParams (dt)\n    18→  c_materials -- MaterialProps[32]\n    19→\"\"\"\n    20→\n    21→from __future__ import annotations\n    22→\n    23→import os\n    24→from typing import Optional\n    25→\n    26→import cupy\n    27→import numpy as np\n    28→\n    29→# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n    30→# CuPy RawModule compilation\n    31→# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n    32→\n    33→_module: Optional[object] = None\n    34→\n    35→\n    36→def _ensure_ptx_if_needed() -> None:\n    37→    \"\"\"Force PTX compilation when GPU arch exceeds NVRTC's max sm target.\"\"\"\n    38→    from cupy.cuda import compiler as _compiler\n    39→    from cupy.cuda import device as _device\n    40→\n    41→    gpu_cc = _device.Device().compute_capability\n    42→    nvrtc_max = _compiler._get_max_compute_capability()\n    43→    if int(gpu_cc) > int(nvrtc_max):\n    44→        _compiler._use_ptx = True\n    45→        if hasattr(_compiler._get_arch_for_options_for_nvrtc, \"_cache\"):\n    46→            _compiler._get_arch_for_options_for_nvrtc._cache = {}\n    47→        if hasattr(_compiler._get_arch, \"_cache\"):\n    48→            _compiler._get_arch._cache = {}\n    49→\n    50→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"374499ef-5ec0-4577-85fa-be8b5d7ef994","uuid":"2efeb6ca-344f-46b6-9182-e76c2de9cbca","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/c/WORK/gpusphsim/fallingsand3d/reactions.py","content":"\"\"\"Reactions kernel: per-particle phase transitions, combustion, and corrosion.\n\nCompiles physics/kernels/reactions.cu via CuPy RawModule and provides\na function to launch K_Reactions which performs:\n  - ICE -> WATER (temp > 273K)\n  - LAVA -> STONE (temp < 900K)\n  - WATER -> SPAWN_GAS flag (temp > 373K)\n  - STEAM -> WATER (temp < 373K)\n  - WOOD/OIL/GUNPOWDER -> FIRE (exposure_heat threshold)\n  - Corrosion: health -= exposure_corrode * dt\n  - GAS lifetime decay -> DEAD when expired\n\nOperates on SORTED arrays, runs after Step1 (which computes exposure)\nand before Step2 (which computes forces).\n\nUses shared constant memory from common.cuh:\n  c_sim       -- SimParams (dt)\n  c_materials -- MaterialProps[32]\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport os\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nimport cupy\nimport numpy as np\n\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# CuPy RawModule compilation\n# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n_module: Optional[object] = None\n\n\ndef _ensure_ptx_if_needed() -> None:\n    \"\"\"Force PTX compilation when GPU arch exceeds NVRTC's max sm target.\"\"\"\n    from cupy.cuda import compiler as _compiler\n    from cupy.cuda import device as _device\n\n    gpu_cc = _device.Device().compute_capability\n    nvrtc_max = _compiler._get_max_compute_capability()\n    if int(gpu_cc) > int(nvrtc_max):\n        _compiler._use_ptx = True\n        if hasattr(_compiler._get_arch_for_options_for_nvrtc, \"_cache\"):\n            _compiler._get_arch_for_options_for_nvrtc._cache = {}\n        if hasattr(_compiler._get_arch, \"_cache\"):\n            _compiler._get_arch._cache = {}\n\n","numLines":50,"startLine":1,"totalLines":178}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01KdohG1dPWp7dtUFfcD3syS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a complete picture. The key insight is that **all kernels read `dt` from `c_sim.dt` constant memory** -- they don't take dt as a kernel argument. So to change dt per-substep, I need to re-upload `c_sim` to all modules that use it. Let me look at how many modules need the upload.\n\nThe approach for US-025:\n\n1. **Add `_compute_adaptive_dt()` to `Simulation`** - computes CFL-based dt from max velocity, acoustic speed, and max viscosity\n2. **Add `_upload_dt()` to `Simulation`** - re-uploads c_sim with new dt to all modules that read c_sim.dt (step1, step2, integrate, reactions, spawn)\n3. **Add controls**: `accuracy` (CFL number), `fixed_dt` toggle, `fixed_dt_value`\n4. **Update `step_frame()`** to use adaptive dt for substep calculation\n5. **Update `main.py`** to show dt in title bar and add keyboard controls\n\nFor the viscous CFL, I need max_eta. Currently eta is computed in the Step2 kernel but not exposed to the host. Since the acceptance criteria says `dt_viscous = accuracy * rho_min * h^2 / max(max_eta, 1e-6)`, and mu(I) can produce eta up to `mu_max=10000`, I can use the mu_max constant as a worst-case for max_eta rather than computing it per-frame (which would need a reduction kernel). This is conservative but correct -- when no GRANULAR particles exist, I can use base_viscosity from the materials table.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the acceptance criteria, the dt_viscous constraint is listed as REQUIRED. Let me think about what to use for max_eta. The simplest approach: scan the active materials to find the max possible viscosity. For FLUID/GAS, it's base_viscosity. For GRANULAR, mu_max=10000 is the worst case. This avoids needing a GPU reduction on eta.\n\nLet me implement this now."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2639,"cache_read_input_tokens":82329,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2639},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"374499ef-5ec0-4577-85fa-be8b5d7ef994","uuid":"ada6f16a-63d6-4a0e-a0c2-235745c94849"}
